*Stage 5: Broker-Side Request Handling (KafkaApis.scala)**\nIn `apache/kafka/core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/KafkaApis.scala`, the `handleProduceRequest()` method at line 388 receives the ProduceRequest and extracts the acks value. The acks value determines response behavior: when acks==0 (line 486, 499), no response is sent immediately. At line 537, the method passes `requiredAcks = produceRequest.acks` to the ReplicaManager's `handleProduceAppend()` method.\n\n**Stage 6: Replica Manager Coordination (ReplicaManager.scala)**\nIn `apache/kafka/core/src/main/scala/kafka/server/ReplicaManager.scala`, the `handleProduceAppend()` method at line 731 receives the requiredAcks parameter. The `isValidRequiredAcks()` method at lines 1363-1364 validates that requiredAcks is one of -1, 1, or 0. The `delayedProduceRequestRequired()` method at line 1355 checks if requiredAcks == -1 to determine if the response should be delayed until all in-sync replicas acknowledge the write. The requiredAcks is then passed to the Partition class for final enforcement.\n\n**Stage 7: Broker Write Acknowledgment (Partition.scala)**\nIn `apache/kafka/core/src/main/scala/kafka/cluster/Partition.scala`, the `appendRecordsToLeader()` method at line 1361 receives the requiredAcks parameter. At line 1370, it checks if `requiredAcks == -1` and verifies that the in-sync replica set size meets the minimum ISR requirement. If requiredAcks == -1 but there aren't enough in-sync replicas, it throws a `NotEnoughReplicasException`, preventing the write and ensuring durability guarantees are met.\n\nThis complete propagation chain ensures that the producer's acks configuration directly controls whether the broker waits for acknowledgments from only the leader (acks=1), all in-sync replicas (acks=-1/\"all\"), or sends no response (acks=0)."
